    "name": "COU1: Non-cannulated construct compression-bending prediction",
    "description": "FEA predicts construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw design under ASTM F1717 static compression-bending. Validated by direct comparison to bench testing (N=11 constructs across two laboratories). Model influence MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence MEDIUM (pedicle screw fracture leads to revision surgery, not death).",
    "intendedUse": "Demonstrate that the FEA modeling framework reproduces experimental compression-bending behavior of a non-cannulated pedicle screw construct within pre-established acceptance bounds (<10% QoI difference, E/uval < 1.96).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "decisionConsequence": "Medium",
    "deviceClass": "Class II"
  },
  "nodes": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/fea-compression-bending-validity-001",
      "type": "Claim",
      "name": "FEA model ensemble adequately predicts compression-bending behavior of the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct",
      "description": "This claim asserts that the FEA modeling framework — comprising independently developed models from FDA, Ansys, and DePuy Synthes — produces predictions of construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement that are within the pre-established acceptance bounds (<10% relative difference, E/uval < 1.96) when compared to ASTM F1717 bench-test results from N=11 constructs tested across two independent laboratories. The body of work underlying this claim includes mesh convergence studies demonstrating discretization error below 2%, material property characterization from coupon testing of Ti-6Al-4V stock, and inter-laboratory comparison showing coefficient of variation below 5% across all three quantities of interest. The claim is considered substantiated by the totality of the simulation and experimental evidence generated during the COU1 validation campaign."
    }
  ],
